"frequently used UVBs in the past (i.e., HM05 and Haardt & Madau"
"(2012) (hereafter HM12)). In Fig. 1, we show the KS19 UVB"
"spectra for U = −1.6, −1.8 and −2.0 along-with the two HM UVBs"
(HM05 and HM12 UVBs) at I = 0.5. The ionization energies
"of different ions (such as H i, Si ii, C ii, Si iii, C iii, Si iv, C iv,"
"He ii, etc.) are marked with vertical lines. As seen in Fig. 1, the"
KS19 UVBs differ significantly from the HM UVBs due to the
different model parameters. The KS19 UVBs exhibit shallower
"slope in comparison to HM05 UVB between 1.5 − 4 Ryd. Hence,"
