5 SUMMARY
We have constructed a sample of C iii absorption systems in optically
thin H i clouds using the COS CGM compendium (CCC) sample
"of L18 at low−I i.e., in the range, 0.2 6 I 6 0.9. We find a total"
of 99 C iii absorption systems from the CCC sample with # (H i)
"(cm−2) in the range, 15.0 6 log N(H i) 6 16.2. The observed"
"N(H i), N(C ii), N(C iii) and column densities of other available"
metal ions along with their associated errors in the measured values
have been adapted from the L18 measurements. We performed
photoionization models for each of these individual C iii systems
using CLOUDY with the updated KS19 UVB (U = −1.8) as the
incident radiation field. We have discussed the implications of the
observed and derived properties of the C iii absorbers systematically.
We have also combined the low−I systems with the high−I C iii
absorption systems from M19 to study the various correlation
between the physical and chemical properties of the optically thin
C iii absorption systems. We have also shown the redshift evolution
of the inferred properties of the C iii absorbers for a wide redshift
range from 0 − 3.3 in compliment with our PI models. Our main
results are as follows:
"• Under the single-phase PI models, the derived hydrogen"
density (=H) of the low−I optically thin C iii absorption systems
ranges from 10−3.4 - 10−1.6 cm−3 with a median value of 10−2.5
cm−3. The median =H of the low−I C iii systems is 0.6 dex higher
than the high−I systems analysed in M19. When we use four
"sub-samples divided in redshift bins, the redshift evolution of =H is"
not monotonous.
"• Metallicity, denoted as [C/H], for the low−I absorbers show"
"a unimodal distribution ranged from -1.6 to 0.4, with a median"
value of -0.46. The distribution of [�/�] for the low and high
redshift C iii systems show a large spread which indicates that the
absorbers are originating from the CGM of host galaxies having
significantly different physical and chemical properties. We found
a strong redshift evolution of [�/�] between low−I and high−I
"absorbers. For the C iii absorbers with # (H i) (cm−2) > 1015, we"
found that the low−I systems have ≈14% absorbers with super
solar metallicity and are more metal enriched than the high−I
counterparts which have only ≈3% super solar systems.
• The over-density of the low−I C iii systems show a range from
3−4.5 with a median value of 3.74 which suggests that the absorbers
are indeed originating from the high over-dense regions like CGM.
The large difference in the median Δ between low−I and high−I
C iii absorbers (≈1.6 dex) is mainly due to the redshift evolution of
"the mean density, =� ."
• The derived line-of-sight thickness (!) of the low−I C iii
systems are ranging from 1.3 pc to 10 kpc with a median value
of 0.6 kpc which is ∼10 times lower than the high−I counterparts.
"The difference in physical parameters (like =H, [C/H], Δ and !) of"
the absorbers suggest a strong redshift evolution of these quantities
between low−I and high−I C iii systems. The distribution of ! is
also significantly different between high−I and low−I C iii systems.
While there are significant numbers of sub-kpc size absorbers (78%)
"present at low−I, only 6% of the absorbers at high−I show such"
sub-kpc scale line-of-sight thickness. This clearly indicates that the
"low−I C iii absorbers are metal enriched, dense and compact clouds"
compared to the high−I counterparts.
• We find a statistically significant anti-correlation between !
"vs. [�/�] for the combined C iii sample, which suggests that the"
"highest metallicity systems are the tiniest in size. However, unlike"
"high−I C iii absorbers, the low−I absorbers are typically smaller"
in size for a given [�/�] as predicted by the toy model used in
M19. This may be due to the slight enhancement in =H at low−I
"and existence of moderate level (i.e., 2f) correlation between =H
and [�/�] in which case the clouds will have a shorter cooling"
time scale (or cooling length). Another possibility of the existence
of such small scale absorbers could be the fragmentation of a larger
high metallicity cloud where the parent cloud is fragmented to
tiny cloudlets to reach pressure equilibrium with its surroundings
efficiently at a final cooling time scale (McCourt et al. 2018).
• We see a clear segregation of the high [�/�] and low
[�/�] branch absorbers occupied in distinct regions of ! vs.
# (C iii) plane consistent with the two populations idea suggested by
Kim et al. (2016). We find that the high−[�/�] branch absorbers
([�/�] > −1.2) with ! < 0.25 kpc show a strong correlation
"with # (C iii), whereas, the low−[�/�] branch absorbers do not"
"exhibit such correlation with # (C iii). However, the high−[�/�]"
branch absorbers are mostly contributed by low−I systems and
"low−[�/�] by high−I systems. Hence, an increased number of C iii"
absorbers spanning in the ! vs. # (C iii) plane uniformly is required
to confirm the existence of a statistically significant bimodality in
metallicity. The results will have implications in understanding the
metal enrichment of the CGM gas and its evolution.
"• Finally, we compare the redshift evolution of [C/H] with the"
"different class of absorption systems (DLAs, s−DLAs, pLLLs and"
"LLSs). As seen in Fig. 9, the metallicity of the C iii absorbers show"
a strong evolution between I ≈ 2.5 and I ≈ 1 while the age of
the Universe was between ≈ 2.5 Gyr to 5.8 Gyr. The evolution
is relatively slower at a later stage of the Universe. The linear
regression fit to the I vs. [�/�] gives a slope −0.41 ± 0.05 with
"intercept, −0.25±0.08. This is steeper than that measured for DLAs"
"(Rafelski et al. 2012; Quiret et al. 2016). Interestingly, the elevated"
slope of the C iii absorbers are within the error range of the measured
slope of s−DLAs from Quiret et al. (2016) and pLLSs + LLSs
"sample across redshift from Lehner et al. (2013, 2016); Wotta et al."
"(2019). However, we reiterate the fact that our results may be illusive"
owing to the lack of the low−=H absorbers at low−I as well as lack
of C iii absorbers in the intermediate redshift (0.9 6 I 6 2.1).
"To make further progress in this field, it will be important to"
search for such C iii absorbers in the intermediate redshift ranges
"(i.e., 1.0 6 I 6 2.0) and at higher redshift (i.e., I > 3) with uniform"
coverage in # (H i). This will allow to create a homogeneous C iii
sample across a large redshift ranges.
